103
00:06:07,968 --> 00:06:10,435
      narrator: book-making     
     has evolved over time,     

104
00:06:10,437 --> 00:06:11,703
          from scrolls          

105
00:06:11,705 --> 00:06:14,240
  to writing on sheets of paper 
         bound together,        

106
00:06:14,242 --> 00:06:16,374
        to the invention        
     of the printing press.     

107
00:06:16,376 --> 00:06:20,312
   people continue to develop   
 new ways of recording history. 

108
00:06:20,314 --> 00:06:22,714
             today,             
  thanks to digital technology, 

109
00:06:22,716 --> 00:06:25,517
        the possibilities       
  of recording the spoken word  

110
00:06:25,519 --> 00:06:27,386
          are endless.          

111
00:06:28,990 --> 00:06:30,656
  a fine book-making specialist 

112
00:06:30,658 --> 00:06:34,125
        makes just a few        
 limited edition books per year,

113
00:06:34,127 --> 00:06:36,962
   using traditional printing   
     and binding techniques.    

114
00:06:39,934 --> 00:06:44,669
  production begins with a case 
      of tiny brass molds.      

115
00:06:44,671 --> 00:06:46,538
            one mold,           
        called a matrix,        

116
00:06:46,540 --> 00:06:50,242
   contains letters, numbers,   
     and punctuation marks.     

117
00:06:52,479 --> 00:06:56,548
a typecasting specialist inserts
 the matrix case into a machine 

118
00:06:56,550 --> 00:06:59,151
        called a monotype       
       composition caster.      

119
00:07:00,955 --> 00:07:05,157
 and melts lead alloy ingots in 
  the machine's gas heated pot. 

120
00:07:07,894 --> 00:07:10,629
      guided by a computer,     
        the machine casts       

121
00:07:10,631 --> 00:07:15,767
     one character at a time    
   for every word of the book.  

122
00:07:15,769 --> 00:07:20,439
  the computer program assigns  
a location code to every matrix.

123
00:07:20,441 --> 00:07:23,308
      to cast a character,      
    the program communicates    

124
00:07:23,310 --> 00:07:26,178
         a specific code        
     through plastic tubes,     

125
00:07:26,180 --> 00:07:29,247
       while puffs of air       
  align that character's matrix 

126
00:07:29,249 --> 00:07:30,982
   with the injection nozzle.   

127
00:07:30,984 --> 00:07:34,319
the nozzle dispenses molten lead
         into the matrix        

128
00:07:34,321 --> 00:07:36,622
    while the machine ejects    
       the cast character       

129
00:07:36,624 --> 00:07:39,524
           onto a tray          
       called the galley.       

130
00:07:39,526 --> 00:07:42,394
    as the lines of text exit   
          the machine,          

131
00:07:42,396 --> 00:07:45,330
 the typecast specialist inserts
         a strip of lead        

132
00:07:45,332 --> 00:07:49,868
    to create spacing, called   
   leading, between each line.  

133
00:07:49,870 --> 00:07:52,738
     he transfers the galley    
       to the press room,       

134
00:07:52,740 --> 00:07:56,141
     where a proofing press     
    spreads ink on the type.    

135
00:07:56,143 --> 00:07:59,411
      he places a sheet of      
    newsprint over the galley   

136
00:07:59,413 --> 00:08:01,880
          and releases          
      an impression roller.     

137
00:08:01,882 --> 00:08:04,282
the roller prints the characters
        on to the paper,        

138
00:08:04,284 --> 00:08:06,051
       generating a proof.      

139
00:08:10,958 --> 00:08:12,691
     meanwhile, a typesetter    

140
00:08:12,693 --> 00:08:15,627
      assembles the larger      
      display copy manually     

141
00:08:15,629 --> 00:08:17,429
  by placing individual letters 

142
00:08:17,431 --> 00:08:19,498
    into a composition stick.   

143
00:08:19,500 --> 00:08:22,968
  this method was used for all  
   copy prior to the invention  

144
00:08:22,970 --> 00:08:26,872
  of the automatic typecasting  
     machines in the 1890s.     

145
00:08:28,976 --> 00:08:31,243
          books printed         
     in large sizes of type     

146
00:08:31,245 --> 00:08:34,346
      must be made entirely     
       by manual typeset.       

147
00:08:37,118 --> 00:08:38,450
         once complete,         

148
00:08:38,452 --> 00:08:41,453
  multiple galleys that make up 
    several pages of the book   

149
00:08:41,455 --> 00:08:44,590
   are placed in a steel frame  
         called a chase         

150
00:08:44,592 --> 00:08:48,861
         and loaded into        
       the printing press.      

151
00:08:48,863 --> 00:08:52,464
    this cylinder press feeds   
  one sheet of paper at a time  

152
00:08:52,466 --> 00:08:56,868
 to grippers that pull the paper
  around a cylindrical roller.  

153
00:08:56,870 --> 00:08:58,737
     as the roller rotates,     

154
00:08:58,739 --> 00:09:01,206
         the paper drops        
      onto the inked type,      

155
00:09:01,208 --> 00:09:04,476
     printing the characters    
         into the sheet.        

156
00:09:04,478 --> 00:09:08,680
    one press sheet typically   
 contains eight pages per side. 

157
00:09:08,682 --> 00:09:11,082
         another machine        
        folds the sheets,       

158
00:09:11,084 --> 00:09:13,619
        then bookbinders        
     manually collate groups    

159
00:09:13,621 --> 00:09:16,155
 of 16 consecutive pages to form

160
00:09:16,157 --> 00:09:19,091
      sections of the book      
       called signatures.       

161
00:09:20,628 --> 00:09:24,096
     next, a bookbinder sews    
     the signatures together    

162
00:09:24,098 --> 00:09:25,030
          one at a time         

163
00:09:25,032 --> 00:09:29,101
        until the book is       
        fully assembled.        

164
00:09:29,103 --> 00:09:32,638
   this method of bookbinding,  
   called smyth sewn binding,   

165
00:09:32,640 --> 00:09:36,841
after its 19th century inventor,
    is of the highest quality   

166
00:09:36,843 --> 00:09:40,245
       because pages can't      
     fall out or be removed.    

167
00:09:40,247 --> 00:09:45,116
                     ♪          

168
00:09:45,118 --> 00:09:46,317
        like the binding,       

169
00:09:46,319 --> 00:09:49,988
        the book cover is       
    meticulously handcrafted.   

170
00:09:49,990 --> 00:09:52,524
     a book binder hot glues    
        a piece of cloth        

171
00:09:52,526 --> 00:09:54,993
    to the back of the cover.   

172
00:09:54,995 --> 00:09:57,062
        the cover is made       
        of flexible paper       

173
00:09:57,064 --> 00:10:01,667
      and thick cardboard.      

174
00:10:01,669 --> 00:10:05,137
   then she flattens the cloth  
          on all sides.         

175
00:10:07,941 --> 00:10:10,876
      using a razor blade,      
  the book binder makes a slit  

176
00:10:10,878 --> 00:10:12,144
         for the cloth,         

177
00:10:12,146 --> 00:10:15,080
       where she'll place       
     a recessed label later.    

178
00:10:15,082 --> 00:10:17,549
     this enables the cloth     
          to spread out         

179
00:10:17,551 --> 00:10:20,686
     and form to the spine's    
         rounded shape.         

180
00:10:20,688 --> 00:10:22,688
      the cloth is pressed      
         firmly against         

181
00:10:22,690 --> 00:10:26,325
 the structural components with 
  a plastic tool called a bone. 

182
00:10:27,827 --> 00:10:29,895
       another book binder      
       attaches the cover       

183
00:10:29,897 --> 00:10:33,565
       to the bound pages,      
     called the book block.     

184
00:10:33,567 --> 00:10:36,502
     first, she applies glue    
       to both components.      

185
00:10:38,972 --> 00:10:42,441
       then she positions       
 the book block on the cover... 

186
00:10:44,845 --> 00:10:46,545
  ...and presses them together. 

187
00:10:50,384 --> 00:10:53,051
       she places the book      
       in a nipping press.      

188
00:10:53,053 --> 00:10:55,453
       that puts pressure       
        around the spine,       

189
00:10:55,455 --> 00:10:58,256
 fusing the book block and cover
            together.           

190
00:10:58,258 --> 00:10:59,991
     then the front and back    
          of the cover          

191
00:10:59,993 --> 00:11:03,061
 are glued to the first and last
       pages of the book.       

192
00:11:04,865 --> 00:11:07,933
      the book then sits in     
    another press overnight,    

193
00:11:07,935 --> 00:11:11,036
 bringing this book-making story
           to a close.          

194
00:11:20,146 --> 00:11:25,550
                     ♪          

195
00:11:25,552 --> 00:11:27,753
  narrator: there's a new class 
     of autonomous vehicles     

196
00:11:27,755 --> 00:11:29,621
   that can travel the ocean.   

197
00:11:29,623 --> 00:11:34,760
    some dive and some sail,    
    but very few can do both.   

198
00:11:34,762 --> 00:11:37,629
   an ocean drone transformer   
      shifts from sailboat      

199
00:11:37,631 --> 00:11:40,899
          to submarine          
    by rearranging its shape    

200
00:11:40,901 --> 00:11:43,101
          and altering          
     its mode of operation.     

201
00:11:46,172 --> 00:11:50,775
      this is an autonomous     
 underwater and surface vehicle.

202
00:11:50,777 --> 00:11:53,378
  it's an information-gathering 
             machine            

203
00:11:53,380 --> 00:11:57,716
  capable of propelling itself  
      over and under waves,     

204
00:11:57,718 --> 00:12:00,485
     using nothing but wind     
        and solar power.        

205
00:12:01,788 --> 00:12:03,655
  to create the vehicle's hull, 

206
00:12:03,657 --> 00:12:07,459
    technicians unroll sheets   
   of fiberglass over a mold,   

207
00:12:07,461 --> 00:12:10,996
     which has been machined    
   from a block of styrofoam.   

208
00:12:10,998 --> 00:12:13,332
     they fiberglass fabric     
          is cut to fit         

209
00:12:13,334 --> 00:12:15,200
    the interior of the hull.   

210
00:12:15,202 --> 00:12:17,869
          thanks to its         
    extraordinary durability,   

211
00:12:17,871 --> 00:12:20,138
    the fiberglass will allow   
         the watercraft         

212
00:12:20,140 --> 00:12:22,808
    to spend months at a time   
             at sea.            

213
00:12:22,810 --> 00:12:23,875
     and it won't interfere     

214
00:12:23,877 --> 00:12:26,011
        with the vessel's       
       electronic signals.      

215
00:12:28,549 --> 00:12:31,750
   technicians carefully tape   
    the material to the mold.   

216
00:12:33,420 --> 00:12:37,422
 this yellow material will allow
  liquid resin to flow easily.  

217
00:12:38,825 --> 00:12:42,160
     then technicians unroll    
     a strip of gray ribbon     

218
00:12:42,162 --> 00:12:44,629
         which will help        
    direct the flow of resin.   

219
00:12:45,432 --> 00:12:48,366
    next, an incision is made   
   in the middle of the ribbon  

220
00:12:48,368 --> 00:12:49,567
         for the nozzle,        

221
00:12:49,569 --> 00:12:51,870
          which will be         
 the entry point for the resin. 

222
00:12:53,373 --> 00:12:56,108
       a layer of plastic       
     is taped onto the hull,    

223
00:12:56,110 --> 00:13:00,045
 which will help to vacuum seal 
     the assembly together.     

224
00:13:00,047 --> 00:13:03,482
    a shut-off valve is added   
  to control the flow of resin. 

225
00:13:07,654 --> 00:13:10,722
       the resin is poured      
        into a container.       

226
00:13:10,724 --> 00:13:13,391
    and as the resin infuses    
         the flow media,        

227
00:13:13,393 --> 00:13:16,127
     it displaces the vacuum    
     until it has completely    

228
00:13:16,129 --> 00:13:20,399
            saturated           
    the fiberglass material.    

229
00:13:20,401 --> 00:13:23,769
the resin is cured for 12 hours.

230
00:13:23,771 --> 00:13:25,937
      the mold splits open      
          at the bottom         

231
00:13:25,939 --> 00:13:30,007
    so technicians can easily   
   release the hull assembly.   

232
00:13:30,009 --> 00:13:32,477
       a technician paints      
       the vehicle's keel,      

233
00:13:32,479 --> 00:13:35,146
        which is made of        
     marine-grade aluminum.     

234
00:13:35,148 --> 00:13:38,750
  the torpedo-shaped keel bulb  
        is made of lead.        

235
00:13:38,752 --> 00:13:41,820
   electric cables run through  
   a hole drilled length-wise   

236
00:13:41,822 --> 00:13:44,556
  down the center of the keel.  

237
00:13:44,558 --> 00:13:47,092
     the interior structure     
      of the vehicle starts     

238
00:13:47,094 --> 00:13:50,696
  as a flat material made from  
   a combination of fiberglass  

239
00:13:50,698 --> 00:13:54,031
      and epoxy which they      
     form into large sheets     

240
00:13:54,033 --> 00:13:57,302
using intense heat and pressure.

241
00:13:57,304 --> 00:14:00,772
    then water jet technology   
    precision cuts the sheets   

242
00:14:00,774 --> 00:14:04,376
    into the required shapes    
           and sizes.           

243
00:14:04,378 --> 00:14:07,178
      technicians assemble      
   the shapes into a structure  

244
00:14:07,180 --> 00:14:08,646
     that supports the hull     

245
00:14:08,648 --> 00:14:10,649
          while housing         
    the vehicle's equipment.    

246
00:14:12,585 --> 00:14:15,653
   in-house technicians build   
   the multiple circuit boards  

247
00:14:15,655 --> 00:14:19,657
    that make up the central    
    processing unit, or cpu.    

248
00:14:19,659 --> 00:14:22,860
 each board controls a separate 
     element of the vehicle,    

249
00:14:22,862 --> 00:14:27,065
 such as the sensors, the wing, 
  or the communications system. 

250
00:14:28,535 --> 00:14:32,137
  electronics and water are not 
    a compatible combination,   

251
00:14:32,139 --> 00:14:35,940
  so the manufacturer designed  
   a water-tight acrylic tube   

252
00:14:35,942 --> 00:14:40,479
  to hold all 10 of the circuit 
  boards that make up the cpu.  

253
00:14:40,481 --> 00:14:43,081
  specialized cable connectors  
          are installed         

254
00:14:43,083 --> 00:14:46,551
      so water doesn't leak     
    through the cover plate.    

255
00:14:46,553 --> 00:14:48,487
  once the enclosure is sealed, 

256
00:14:48,489 --> 00:14:51,556
     technicians vacuum out     
        flammable oxygen        

257
00:14:51,558 --> 00:14:56,361
    and pump in non-flammable   
    gases to protect the cpu.   

258
00:14:56,363 --> 00:14:58,696
          a technician          
      prepares the battery,     

259
00:14:58,698 --> 00:15:01,400
    which is an off-the-shelf   
        lithium ion unit.       

260
00:15:04,505 --> 00:15:08,372
a battery housing is 3-d printed
          out of a.b.s.         

261
00:15:08,374 --> 00:15:10,641
     and infused with epoxy     
            to ensure           

262
00:15:10,643 --> 00:15:13,645
      that it's completely      
          water tight.          

263
00:15:13,647 --> 00:15:16,113
   next, a technician installs  
           the battery          

264
00:15:16,115 --> 00:15:18,650
     in its designated spot.    

265
00:15:18,652 --> 00:15:21,119
         solar panels on        
      the vehicle's surface     

266
00:15:21,121 --> 00:15:23,455
  will recharge the batteries.  

267
00:15:23,457 --> 00:15:26,524
        a hose will allow       
    the cpu to transfer water   

268
00:15:26,526 --> 00:15:28,860
from one ballast tank to another

269
00:15:28,862 --> 00:15:32,197
      to control the boat's     
  up and down motion or pitch.  

270
00:15:33,333 --> 00:15:35,734
       the vehicle's tails      
        serve as housings       

271
00:15:35,736 --> 00:15:38,937
         for the backup         
 communications antenna system. 

272
00:15:38,939 --> 00:15:42,674
  in stealth mode, the vehicle  
 can sit below the water surface

273
00:15:42,676 --> 00:15:46,010
       with only its tails      
        above the waves.        

274
00:15:46,012 --> 00:15:48,280
      designed to fold down     
     and tuck into the body     

275
00:15:48,282 --> 00:15:51,416
         of the vehicle,        
   the rigid wing multi-tasks   

276
00:15:51,418 --> 00:15:53,818
     as the primary antenna     
          and the sail,         

277
00:15:53,820 --> 00:15:57,355
    which propels the vehicle   
     when it's above water.     

278
00:15:57,357 --> 00:15:59,691
    due to its user-friendly    
           technology,          

279
00:15:59,693 --> 00:16:01,626
     an operator can program    
            a mission           

280
00:16:01,628 --> 00:16:04,029
           at any time          
        from any location       

281
00:16:04,031 --> 00:16:06,531
     via satellite or wi-fi.    

282
00:16:13,974 --> 00:16:19,577
                     ♪          

283
00:16:19,579 --> 00:16:21,846
   narrator: the first jigsaw   
       puzzle was invented      

284
00:16:21,848 --> 00:16:24,181
       in europe in 1760.       

285
00:16:24,183 --> 00:16:25,917
   nearly two centuries later,  

286
00:16:25,919 --> 00:16:29,387
  a canadian inventor reshaped  
      the popular pastime.      

287
00:16:29,389 --> 00:16:33,458
his puzzle pieces, made of thick
   foam rather than cardboard,  

288
00:16:33,460 --> 00:16:36,060
      could stand upright,      
       turning the puzzle       

289
00:16:36,062 --> 00:16:37,929
  into a three-dimension model. 

290
00:16:39,566 --> 00:16:43,802
    constructing a 3-d puzzle   
   yields impressive results.   

291
00:16:43,804 --> 00:16:48,206
     to do so, two 800-piece    
 puzzle sets are used to create 

292
00:16:48,208 --> 00:16:52,944
        this spectacular        
         castle replica.        

293
00:16:52,946 --> 00:16:55,413
 an industrial designer creates 
          the puzzle's          

294
00:16:55,415 --> 00:16:57,415
  three-dimensional structure.  

295
00:16:57,417 --> 00:17:01,152
 an illustrator uses techniques,
     such as visual textures    

296
00:17:01,154 --> 00:17:04,222
    and shading, to transform   
          flat graphics         

297
00:17:04,224 --> 00:17:07,091
    into a three-dimensional    
           rendering.           

298
00:17:07,093 --> 00:17:11,028
the industrial designer prepares
the printing and cutting layout,

299
00:17:11,030 --> 00:17:14,165
       fitting up to three      
       puzzles per sheet.       

300
00:17:14,167 --> 00:17:17,568
   the puzzle pieces are made   
        from rigid foam.        

301
00:17:17,570 --> 00:17:19,504
            the foam            
   is specifically engineered   

302
00:17:19,506 --> 00:17:22,774
   to be chemically compatible  
     with the paper graphics    

303
00:17:22,776 --> 00:17:26,244
    and proprietary adhesive.   

304
00:17:26,246 --> 00:17:28,980
     a technician feeds one     
         sheet at a time        

305
00:17:28,982 --> 00:17:31,983
     into a custom designed     
       lamination machine.      

306
00:17:31,985 --> 00:17:34,052
        the first station       
        spreads hot glue        

307
00:17:34,054 --> 00:17:36,087
 over the top of the foam sheet.

308
00:17:37,524 --> 00:17:40,525
      an automated arm with     
       vacuum suction cups      

309
00:17:40,527 --> 00:17:42,860
      lifts a single sheet      
        of printed paper        

310
00:17:42,862 --> 00:17:46,864
        and places it on        
   the glue-coated foam sheet.  

311
00:17:46,866 --> 00:17:49,467
      as soon as the paper      
      adheres to the foam,      

312
00:17:49,469 --> 00:17:52,237
       the she is released      
     from the suction cups.     

313
00:17:55,542 --> 00:17:57,675
       then the foam moves      
         under a roller         

314
00:17:57,677 --> 00:17:59,544
  that presses down the paper.  

315
00:18:01,748 --> 00:18:04,882
      as the laminated foam     
       exits the machine,       

316
00:18:04,884 --> 00:18:08,486
    a technician rolls a tube   
   over the foam, pressing out  

317
00:18:08,488 --> 00:18:10,088
    any remaining air bubbles   

318
00:18:10,090 --> 00:18:12,423
       to ensure the paper      
         adheres fully.         

319
00:18:12,425 --> 00:18:14,825
                     ♪          

320
00:18:14,827 --> 00:18:17,762
    in the development phase,   
     the industrial designer    

321
00:18:17,764 --> 00:18:19,297
      assembled a blueprint     

322
00:18:19,299 --> 00:18:21,566
    for how the puzzle pieces   
         would be shaped        

323
00:18:21,568 --> 00:18:23,702
          and laid out.         

324
00:18:23,704 --> 00:18:25,770
           that design          
       went to a toolmaker      

325
00:18:25,772 --> 00:18:28,173
  who produced a corresponding  
           cutting die          

326
00:18:28,175 --> 00:18:29,874
      out of steel knives.      

327
00:18:32,845 --> 00:18:35,780
       the die is mounted       
   inside the cutting machine.  

328
00:18:35,782 --> 00:18:37,582
                     ♪          

329
00:18:37,584 --> 00:18:41,052
 a technician feeds the machine 
    one laminated foam sheet    

330
00:18:41,054 --> 00:18:43,455
           at a time,           
        paper side down.        

331
00:18:45,458 --> 00:18:47,725
          grippers grab         
     the edge of the paper,     

332
00:18:47,727 --> 00:18:50,261
        pulling the sheet       
        into the machine.       

333
00:18:50,263 --> 00:18:52,530
     the cutting die slices     
        the puzzle pieces       

334
00:18:52,532 --> 00:18:53,565
         into the foam.         

335
00:18:55,335 --> 00:18:58,403
even though the cutting pressure
      compresses the foam,      

336
00:18:58,405 --> 00:19:02,374
  it immediately bounces back,  
    keeping the sheet intact.   

337
00:19:04,277 --> 00:19:06,411
    thanks to a high-quality    
          rubber sheet          

338
00:19:06,413 --> 00:19:08,813
  inserted between the blades,  

339
00:19:08,815 --> 00:19:12,083
   the pieces don't get stuck   
           in the die.          

340
00:19:12,085 --> 00:19:14,686
        the stiff rubber        
    provides counter-pressure   

341
00:19:14,688 --> 00:19:19,624
         to help remove         
         the foam sheet.        

342
00:19:19,626 --> 00:19:22,827
  if the sheet has two or three 
     puzzles printed on it,     

343
00:19:22,829 --> 00:19:25,697
         the cutting die        
         separates them.        

344
00:19:25,699 --> 00:19:28,233
    then a technician places    
           the puzzle           

345
00:19:28,235 --> 00:19:30,501
       on a semi-automatic      
          conveyor belt         

346
00:19:30,503 --> 00:19:33,571
          that moves it         
   to the dismantling machine.  

347
00:19:33,573 --> 00:19:36,373
       the machine infuses      
    the die-cut puzzle sheet    

348
00:19:36,375 --> 00:19:37,842
           with steam.          

349
00:19:37,844 --> 00:19:40,245
       the steam prevents       
       static electricity,      

350
00:19:40,247 --> 00:19:43,114
       which causes pieces      
        to cling together       

351
00:19:43,116 --> 00:19:46,117
or to the inside of the machine.

352
00:19:46,119 --> 00:19:48,453
           the machine          
      separates the pieces.     

353
00:19:48,455 --> 00:19:53,124
       and dispenses them       
       into a puzzle box.       

354
00:19:53,126 --> 00:19:55,994
 a technician adds the standard 
       instructions sheet,      

355
00:19:55,996 --> 00:20:00,865
       and seals the box.       

356
00:20:00,867 --> 00:20:02,801
      the instructions are      
       in black and white,      

357
00:20:02,803 --> 00:20:05,170
        but can be viewed       
        in color online.        

358
00:20:06,473 --> 00:20:10,007
    the first step is to sort   
 the pieces by color and design 

359
00:20:10,009 --> 00:20:13,144
     and set aside the ones     
      marked with a red dot     

360
00:20:13,146 --> 00:20:15,814
        which is part of        
   the manufacturing process,   

361
00:20:15,816 --> 00:20:18,483
     not the puzzle itself.     

362
00:20:18,485 --> 00:20:22,887
  the next step is to assemble  
 the puzzle, section by section.

363
00:20:22,889 --> 00:20:24,722
   all the sections are flat,   

364
00:20:24,724 --> 00:20:28,026
     so the final step is to    
    attach the flat sections    

365
00:20:28,028 --> 00:20:31,829
       to make the puzzle       
       three-dimensional.       

366
00:20:31,831 --> 00:20:33,565
  for an additional challenge,  

367
00:20:33,567 --> 00:20:36,301
          you can forgo         
  the step-by-step instructions 

368
00:20:36,303 --> 00:20:39,137
        and refer only to       
     the photos on the box.     

369
00:20:40,573 --> 00:20:42,841
        if you happen to        
      lose a puzzle piece,      

370
00:20:42,843 --> 00:20:45,043
          you can go to         
      the company's website     

371
00:20:45,045 --> 00:20:47,578
       to trace the number      
     of your missing piece,     

372
00:20:47,580 --> 00:20:50,248
 then order a new piece online. 

373
00:20:50,250 --> 00:20:51,850
 the company will mail it to you

374
00:20:51,852 --> 00:20:53,785
         so that you can        
      complete your puzzle.     

375
00:20:55,455 --> 00:20:57,588
      unlike a traditional      
          flat puzzle,          

376
00:20:57,590 --> 00:21:03,594
  you can move your 3-d puzzle  
    without it falling apart.   

377
00:21:03,596 --> 00:21:05,597
   it takes four to six months  

378
00:21:05,599 --> 00:21:09,801
      to develop and design     
   this incredible 3-d puzzle.  

379
00:21:09,803 --> 00:21:12,003
     now it's time to spend     
           even longer          

380
00:21:12,005 --> 00:21:14,239
  piecing this puzzle together. 

